Horace addresses this ode to the Muse Melpomene, as the patroness of lyric poetry. He thanks the Muses for their fa- vours to him even from the hour of his birth3 and seems to im- ply that he received in the first moments of life whatever dis- tinguished him afterwards.. The ode is written with so much beauty and feeling, that Scaliger says he would rather be the author of it, than be the king of Arragon.
